A%2F%2Feucalyptus.atlassian.net%2Fsecure%2Fuseravatar%3Fsize%3Dxsmall%26avatarId%3D10100%26noRedirect%3Dtrue","32x32":"https://avatar-cdn.atlassian.com/8962f6c2075b2cf80ed6daccff85c8a7?s=32&d=https%3A%2F%2Feucalyptus.atlassian.net%2Fsecure%2Fuseravatar%3Fsize%3Dmedium%26avatarId%3D10100%26noRedirect%3Dtrue"},"displayName":"Keri Meredith","active":true,"timeZone":"America/Los_Angeles"},"updated":"2016-09-08T16:06:34.769-0500","status":{"self":"https://eucalyptus.atlassian.net/rest/api/2/status/5","description":"A resolution has been taken, and it is awaiting verification by reporter. From here issues are either reopened, or are closed.","iconUrl":"https://eucalyptus.atlassian.net/images/icons/statuses/resolved.png","name":"Resolved","id":"5","statusCategory":{"self":"https://eucalyptus.atlassian.net/rest/api/2/statuscategory/3","id":3,"key":"done","colorName":"green","name":"Done"}},"components":[{"self":"https://eucalyptus.atlassian.net/rest/api/2/component/10203","id":"10203","name":"Installation Guide"}],"timeoriginalestimate":null,"customfield_13000":null,"description":"In here:\r\nhttp://packages.release.eucalyptus-systems.com/documentation/origin/master/#install-guide/rhel7_upgrade_non_nc_hosts.html\r\n\r\n{quote}\r\nTo upgrade a non-NC host machine to RHEL 7\r\n{quote}\r\n\r\nAs written, you install Euca by going through the fresh Installation steps _for each host_. That's not right, I've discovered: You need to go through the install steps once, which includes installing Euca on all hosts. (But in this case, we skip the parts for NCs because we've already installed 4.3 on RHEL7 for them.)\r\n\r\nFor example: It's wrong to go through the install steps for just the CLC+SC+CC host, all the way through, then go through the steps again for the UFS host. That would leave your cloud in a corrupted state (due to how/when you recover cloud data), which happened to me, following my own instructions as currently documented (oops!). I think people have been doing it the right way anyway, not strictly following the docs here, which is why we haven't had problems.\r\n\r\nBut we need to fix it, my try at it here, changes in {color:#d04437}red{color}:\r\n(It also simplifies the process)\r\n----\r\nh3. To upgrade {color:#d04437}the set of non-NC host machines {color}to RHEL 7\r\n\r\n#    Shut down {color:#d04437}all non-NC host machines{color} gracefully.\r\n   -{color:#d04437} This is for the benefit of the other Eucalyptus hosts in the cloud.{color}-\r\n#    Replace {color:#d04437}each non-NC {color}host machine's operating system with RHEL 7.\r\n    This is a clean install of the OS.\r\n    See Install RHEL 7 on a Eucalyptus 4.3 Host Machine.\r\n#    Install Eucalyptus 4.3.\r\n    This is a clean install of Eucalyptus {color:#d04437}on the set of non-NC host machines together. -, specifically for this host machine.-{color}\r\n    See Configure Dependencies through Set Up Security Groups.\r\n    Install the same set of Eucalyptus services {color:#d04437}on the same set of hosts {color}you had running prior to the RHEL 7 upgrade.\r\n#    {color:#d04437}_(Remove this bullet because you'll move the info about recovering cloud data per DOC-1921)_ -Recover the host machine's cloud state. This restores the host's cloud state after the clean RHEL 7 and clean Eucalyptus installs. See Recover Cloud Data.- {color}  \r\n#    Verify that the clean installs worked and that the {color:#d04437}overall {color}cloud state has been recovered properly.\r\n#    {color:#d04437}-Repeat this procedure for all Eucalyptus host machines.-{color}\r\n\r\n{color:#d04437}Now that you have upgraded the set of non-NC hosts, and previously upgraded all NC hosts, your cloud is ready for production. \r\n-The upgraded host machine is now ready for production.-{color}\r\n\r\n----\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n","customfield_13200":null,"customfield_11300":null,"customfield_11500":{"self":"https://eucalyptus.atlassian.net/rest/api/2/user?username=kmeredith","name":"kmeredith","key":"kme